I tried with concate function to combine all the datasets but it is not merging the columns, just coping the data sets one after one. Due to this its creating n number of nans.¶

Finally I found the merge function, it is removing the all duplicates and merging the columns.¶

Merge all data sets in to one, by the order of matching features¶

After I tried with all possibilites I found this proper order to merge the all datasets in to one

In [68]:
df = pd.merge(df7,df8)
df = pd.merge(df,df6)
df = pd.merge(df,df4)
df = pd.merge(df,df5)
df = pd.merge(df,df2)
df = pd.merge(df,df3)
df = pd.merge(df,df1)

In [95]:
def trans_box(i):
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,8),facecolor='white')
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)
    plt.subplot(2,3,1)
    sns.boxplot(data=df_num[i],orient='h')
    plt.title('Original',fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.xlabel(i,fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.subplot(2,3,2)
    sns.boxplot(data=np.sqrt(df_num[i]),orient='h')
    plt.title('Sqroot',fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.xlabel(i,fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.subplot(2,3,3)
    sns.boxplot(data=(df_num[i])**2,orient='h')

In [99]:
def df_out(col):
    Q3,Q1 = np.nanpercentile(col,[75,25])
    IQR = Q3-Q1
    UL = Q3+1.5*IQR
    LL = Q1-1.5*IQR
    return UL,LL
In [100]:
# First replacing the Outliers in to 'Null' values
for column in df_num.columns:
    UL, LL = df_out(df[column])
    df[column]= np.where((df[column] > UL)|(df[column] < LL),np.nan, df[column])

def trans_kde(i):
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,8),facecolor='white')
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)
    plt.subplot(2,3,1)
    sns.kdeplot(data=df_num[i])
    plt.title('Original',fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.xlabel(i,fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.subplot(2,3,2)
    sns.kdeplot(data=np.sqrt(df_num[i]))
    plt.title('Sqroot',fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.xlabel(i,fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.subplot(2,3,3)
    sns.kdeplot(data=(df_num[i])**2)
    plt.title('Square',fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.xlabel(i,fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.subplot(2,3,4)
    sns.kdeplot(data=np.log(df_num[i]))
    plt.title('Log',fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.xlabel(i,fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.subplot(2,3,5)
    sns.kdeplot(data=np.cbrt(df_num[i]))
    plt.title('Cuberoot',fontdict={'fontsize':15})
    plt.xlabel(i,fontdict={'fontsize':15})

Hypothesis Testing¶

Normality Test¶

Hypothesis testing on Normality using ShapiroTest Null Hypothesis H0: Gaussian Distribution: If P>0.05 accept H0 Alternative Hypothesis H1: Not a Gaussian Distribution: If P<0.05 accept H1
In [132]:
from scipy.stats import shapiro
In [133]:
stat, p = shapiro(df.Loan_Default)
print('stat=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat, p))
if p > 0.05:
    print('Probably Gaussian')
else:
    print('Probably not Gaussian')

stat=0.512, p=0.000
Probably not Gaussian

Hece P value is < 0.05 we reject the Null Hypothesis So we conlude that Predicted value is not following the Normal Distribution Hence we go for the Non-Peramateric test to know the relation between Targeted and Independent Variables.

Tests for Relationship between two variables

  1. For Categorical - Chi-squared test
  2. For Continious - Spearmans Correlation Co- efficient
Hypothesis testing for relation Null Hypothesis H0: There is no relation b/w independent variables and Target/dependent variable 'Loan_Default'. If P>0.05 accept H0 Alternative Hypothesis H1: There is a relation b/w independent variables and Target/dependent variable 'Loan_Default'.If P<0.05 accept H1

Hence we can remove these features from our dataset

from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
